 socially. He explains how BRAC has employed western ideas, theories, and philosophies of agency when engaging in development interventions in even the remotest villages, seeking to transform social structures, women's status, and the local polity. The resulting intermingling of exogenous perspectives with local knowledge leads to a degree of inconsistency and dissonance within BRAC's own operations, while generating opposition from local commoners and elites. Cautionary yet hopeful, the book advocates greater cultural sensitivity as a way to mitigate conflict between BRAC and the constituencies it serves.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aBRAC (Organization). 0aNon-governmental organizationszBangladesh. 0aRural development - Social aspects - Bangladesh. 0aRural developmentxSocial aspectszBangladesh. 0aWomenzBangladeshxSocial conditions. 4aAnthropology and Archaeology : Anthropology. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Studies. 4aBusiness and Economics : Economy and Society. 4aGender and Sexuality : Women's Studies. 4aPolitics and Law : Comparative Politics. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2015z978311149061840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438457857423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438457857/original  a978-3-11-149061-8  SUNY Press eBook Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles